      <div class="gr-stats gr-stats-col">
        <div class="gr-stat"><span class="gr-stat-number">{{ CP.stats.voters }}</span><span class="gr-stat-label">voters</span></div>
        <div class="gr-stat"><span class="gr-stat-number">{{ CP.stats.total_votes_display }}</span><span class="gr-stat-label">votes cast</span></div>
        <div class="gr-stat"><span class="gr-stat-number">{{ CP.stats.statements }}</span><span class="gr-stat-label">statements</span></div>
        <div class="gr-stat"><span class="gr-stat-number">{{ CP.stats.live_statements }}</span><span class="gr-stat-label">written live by participants</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 0: the question + the hook ---------- #}
  <section aria-label="The deliberation question" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">The question put to the room</p>
      <p class="gr-hero-question mb-6">“What would AI governance need to do so that everyone here felt seen by AI?”</p>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-4">Faith leaders, peacebuilders, technologists, and civil-society voices across four-plus continents answered it together — writing statements and voting on each other's, live and for 24 hours after.</p>
      <p class="st-hook">We asked how AI could see everyone. The room answered a question we didn't ask — whether it should.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 1 ---------- #}
  <section id="act1" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">Act 1</p>
      <h2 class="mb-4">Recognition without intimacy</h2>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-6">The conveners treated “being seen” as one thing. The room took it apart into two — and gave them opposite verdicts. Being seen <em>as a community</em> — accurately represented, with the power to correct the record — was the event's strongest consensus. Being seen <em>as a person</em> — intimately known — was refused.</p>
      <div class="st-cards st-cards-2 mb-6">
        {{ evcard(2, "Seen as a community: the strongest consensus of the event") }}
        {{ evcard(4, "Seen as a person: rejected") }}
      </div>
      <p class="st-takeaway">Representation is a collective right; intimate knowledge of individuals is a threat. The personalization-versus-protection trade-off wasn't balanced by the room — it was dissolved.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 2 ---------- #}
  <section id="act2" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2 gr-feature">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">Act 2</p>
      <h2 class="mb-4">The divide the algorithm couldn't hold</h2>

      <p class="gr-prose mb-4">The room's visible fight is about whose job representation is:</p>
      <div class="st-cards st-cards-2 mb-8">
        {{ evcard(9, "The fight: is reflecting every culture's values AI's job at all?") }}
        <div>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Bloc A leans agree ({{ ST["9"].blocs.A.agrees }}/{{ ST["9"].blocs.A.disagrees }}/{{ ST["9"].blocs.A.passes }}); bloc C rejects ({{ ST["9"].blocs.C.agrees }}/{{ ST["9"].blocs.C.disagrees }}/{{ ST["9"].blocs.C.passes }}). That is the divide the clustering algorithm sees — the one that defines the blocs.</p>
          <p class="text-size--1">But a second divide ignores that fight entirely: whether AI belongs <em>close to you</em>. It shows up in three statements written live in the room:</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="st-cards st-cards-3 mb-8">
        {{ evcard(23, "Don't see me") }}
        {{ evcard(30, "The lonely friend") }}
        {{ evcard(55, "Junk food") }}
      </div>

      <div class="st-bigfacts mb-8">
        <div class="st-bigfact">
          <span class="gr-stat-number">{{ CP.cohorts.both_23_and_30.n }}</span>
          <p class="text-size--2">participants agreed with <em>both</em> “I don't want to feel seen by AI” and the lonely-friend statement — {{ CP.cohorts.both_23_and_30.by_bloc.C }} from bloc C and {{ CP.cohorts.both_23_and_30.by_bloc.A }} from bloc A: both sides of the main fight.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="st-bigfact">
          <span class="gr-stat-number">{{ ST["23"].blocs.C.agrees }}–{{ ST["23"].blocs.C.disagrees }}</span>
          <p class="text-size--2">how “I don't want to feel seen by AI” splits <em>inside</em> bloc C (agree–disagree, plus {{ ST["23"].blocs.C.passes }} passes). The divide runs through the majority bloc, not between the blocs.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="mb-2">Watch the algorithm lose it</h3>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-4">At 09:00, Pol.is clustered these voters into four groups — including an 8-member group of the participants most comfortable with AI closeness. Six hours and 106 votes later, <strong>with not a single vote changed</strong>, the reclustering dissolved that group: {{ CP.crosswalk.b0900_destinations.C }} of its members were absorbed into bloc C, {{ CP.crosswalk.b0900_destinations.A }} into bloc A, {{ CP.crosswalk.b0900_destinations.other }} into the leftover pair. The divide went underground.</p>

      <figure class="st-figure mb-4">
        <div class="st-diagram">
          <div>
            <p class="gr-kicker mb-1">09:00 — four groups</p>
            {{ diagramPanel(CP.diagram.left, "The 09:00 clustering: four groups of dots — group A with " + CP.crosswalk.g0900_sizes.A + " members, the highlighted 8-member closeness-comfortable group B, group C with " + CP.crosswalk.g0900_sizes.C + ", a single-member group D, plus unclustered participants and one who joined later. Dots outlined in black are the closeness cohort.") }}
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="gr-kicker mb-1">15:05 — two blocs (same people, same votes)</p>
            {{ diagramPanel(CP.diagram.right, "The 15:05 clustering of the same participants: bloc A with " + CP.crosswalk.g1505_sizes.A + " members shown, bloc C with " + CP.crosswalk.g1505_sizes.C + ", and a small set of others. The outlined closeness-cohort dots are now scattered inside the blocs rather than forming their own group.") }}
          </div>
        </div>
        <figcaption class="st-figcaption mt-2">
          The same {{ CP.diagram.left | length }} participants, twice. Colors are the machine's groupings (left: 09:00, with the 8-member closeness-comfortable group in orange; right: 15:05). <strong>Black outlines mark the closeness cohort</strong> — the {{ CP.cohorts.closeness.n }} people who, by their own votes, want AI closeness ({{ CP.cohorts.closeness.by_bloc.C }} now inside bloc C, {{ CP.cohorts.closeness.by_bloc.A }} in bloc A, {{ CP.cohorts.closeness.by_bloc.other }} in the leftover pair). At 09:00 most had their own group; at 15:05 the outlines are scattered through the blocs. Grey dots are the leftover pair and unclustered voters — never a faction.
        </figcaption>
      </figure>

      <aside class="st-caveat mb-6" aria-label="What opinion clustering is and why it moves">
        <h3 class="mb-2">What just happened, in plain language</h3>
        <p>Pol.is groups people by the <em>overall similarity</em> of their voting patterns — it doesn't know which disagreements matter to you. With ~37 voters, one or two borderline people can tip the math from “four groups” to “two,” the way a photo grid re-sorts when you add a few pictures. Nothing was wrong with the votes; instability at this scale is a property of the method, not an error in the data. That is why this page anchors its claims in <strong>cohorts defined by votes</strong> (which survive any reclustering), not in the machine's group labels.</p>
      </aside>

      <p class="st-takeaway">Some divides are too cross-cutting for clustering to hold: they run through communities, not between them. That is exactly what the ballot's tension items exist to measure.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 3 ---------- #}
  <section id="act3" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">Act 3</p>
      <h2 class="mb-4">Stricter rules than we proposed — including on themselves</h2>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-6">The room didn't just accept protective design — it demanded it over its own preferences. The anchor statement says “even if users want that closeness,” and the demand binds its own authors: of the <strong>{{ CP.cohorts.closeness.n }} participants in the closeness cohort</strong> — the people who, by their own votes, want AI intimacy — <strong>{{ CP.cohorts.closeness.on_16.endorsed }} endorsed it and only {{ CP.cohorts.closeness.on_16.opposed }} opposed</strong>. Users petitioning for protective design against their own stated preferences.</p>
      <div class="st-cards st-cards-2 mb-6">
        {{ evcard(16, "Protect us from over-dependence — even if we ask for the closeness") }}
        {{ evcard(51, "Regulate the psychology of use, not just the model") }}
      </div>
      <p class="st-takeaway">And the room out-wrote its conveners: <strong>{{ CP.top10_live }} of the ten strongest cross-bloc consensus statements were written live by participants</strong>, not seeded — in order: {% for t in CP.top10_consensus %}[{{ t.id }}] {{ t.source }}{% if not loop.last %}, {% endif %}{% endfor %}.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 4: ledger ---------- #}
  <section id="act4" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">Act 4</p>
      <h2 class="mb-4">The ledger of new ideas</h2>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-6">Ideas that entered the world in this room — written live, voted up, and carried into the draft ballot in Act 5.</p>
      <div class="st-ledger">
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R10</p>
          {{ evcard(23, "The right not to be known") }}
          {{ evcard(30, "…and the loss it protects against") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R9</p>
          {{ evcard(26, "Homogenization as a governance harm") }}
          {{ evcard(70, "…the tyranny of the majority, aggregated") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R7</p>
          {{ evcard(47, "Worldview provenance disclosure") }}
          {{ evcard(48, "…because AI is not neutral") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R2</p>
          {{ evcard(51, "The psychology of use as a regulatory object") }}
          {{ evcard(66, "…including narratives that shame") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R4</p>
          {{ evcard(53, "Non-substitutable care") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R8</p>
          {{ evcard(65, "What we confide deserves protection") }}
          {{ evcard(67, "…and surveillance named as a first-order harm") }}
        </div>
        <div>
          <p class="st-ledger-route mb-1">→ ballot item R5</p>
          {{ evcard(80, "Learning to use AI healthily can't be outsourced to model changes") }}
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- act 5: one diagnosis, two remedies ---------- #}
  <section id="act5" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-kicker mb-2">Act 5 · The conclusion</p>
      <h2 class="mb-4">One diagnosis, two remedies, one condition</h2>

      <h3 class="mb-2">Both blocs, same direction: the red lines</h3>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-4">Before the room divides, it agrees on what it refuses. These rejections are the floor of the room, not one group's position:</p>
      <div class="st-cards st-cards-2 st-strip mb-4">
        {{ evcard(4, "Intimate personalization: rejected — zero agreement in bloc A") }}
        {{ evcard(67, "Surveillance: a first-order harm") }}
        {{ evcard(36, "AI that flatters instead of challenges") }}
        {{ evcard(26, "The flattening of voice") }}
      </div>
      <div class="mb-10">
        <p class="gr-counts mb-2">Adjacent red lines, same direction:</p>
        <div class="st-cards st-cards-2">
          {{ evcard(65, "Who accesses what we confide") }}
          {{ evcard(42, "Formulaic voice") }}
        </div>
      </div>

      <h3 class="mb-4">The fork in the remedy</h3>
      <div class="st-remedies mb-4">
        <div class="gr-group-col gr-border-C">
          <h4 class="font-bold mb-1"><span class="gr-text-C">Authorship</span> — bloc C, {{ CP.method.blocs.C }} people</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-3">Remake AI on communities' own terms. This is the one affirmative program in the data with broad support and no organized opposition.</p>
          <div class="flex flex-col gap-2">
            {{ evcard(3, "Communities building AI tuned to their values") }}
            {{ evcard(17, "Community-trained AI deepening, not replacing, practice") }}
            {{ evcard(6, "Members see their own data first") }}
            {{ evcard(35, "An indigenous-designed AI educating the mainstream") }}
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="gr-group-col gr-border-A">
          <h4 class="font-bold mb-1"><span class="gr-text-A">Boundaries</span> — bloc A, {{ CP.method.blocs.A }} people</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-3">Whoever builds it, some human ground stays reserved. Bloc A endorses regulation ({{ ST["21"].blocs.A.agrees }}/{{ ST["21"].blocs.A.disagrees }}/{{ ST["21"].blocs.A.passes }}), contestability ({{ ST["2"].blocs.A.agrees }}/{{ ST["2"].blocs.A.disagrees }}/{{ ST["2"].blocs.A.passes }}), and member data rights ({{ ST["6"].blocs.A.agrees }}/{{ ST["6"].blocs.A.disagrees }}/{{ ST["6"].blocs.A.passes }}) — its distinctive position is about where AI belongs, not whether it should exist.</p>
          <div class="flex flex-col gap-2 mb-3">
            {{ evcard(9, "It isn't AI's job to reflect every culture's values") }}
            {{ evcard(13, "Some questions belong only to a person") }}
            {{ evcard(78, "The only bloc to defend the “human essence” posture") }}
          </div>
          <p class="gr-counts mb-1">Bloc A on the authorship program — abstention, not objection (passes shown as the pale middle band, distinct from striped disagreement):</p>
          {% for sid in [3, 35] %}
          {% set t = ST["" ~ sid].blocs.A %}
          <div class="gr-mini">
            <span class="gr-counts">[{{ sid }}]</span>
            {{ bar(t, "Bloc A on statement " + sid) }}
            <span class="gr-counts">{{ t.passes }} of {{ t.votes }} passes{{ thin(t) }}</span>
          </div>
          {% endfor %}
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="st-takeaway mb-10">The boundary-keepers don't oppose communal AI — they abstain from it. An abstention is an invitation to demonstrate, not a door closed.</p>

      <h3 class="mb-2">The condition of compatibility</h3>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-6">The two remedies are compatible on exactly one condition: that communal AI honors the red lines — including the right not to be seen. Ballot item <a class="underline" href="#ballot">R10</a> is that condition made concrete; <a class="underline" href="#ballot">R4's ⚑</a> marks the other tension the quadratic-voting stage will price. Split spending on the flagged items is the intended signal, not a flaw.</p>

      <h4 id="ballot" class="font-bold mb-2">The draft ballot (R1–R10)</h4>
      <ol class="st-ballot mb-4">
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R1 — Contestability &amp; answerability</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Communities get a binding channel to challenge how AI represents their tradition and get errors fixed; whoever sets an AI's values answers to the people affected.</p>
          {{ evcard(2, "Grounding: challenge and correct") }}{{ evcard(21, "Grounding: regulation is a necessity") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R2 — The psychology of use as a regulatory object</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Governance engages how systems respond to distress, shame, and attachment — measured and regulated, not left to product choice.</p>
          {{ evcard(7, "Grounding: measure responses to distress") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R3 — Anti-dependency &amp; anti-manipulation by design</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Systems designed against emotional over-dependence and manipulation, even when users want the closeness.</p>
          {{ evcard(5, "Grounding: understanding that can't manipulate") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R4 — Non-substitutable care <span class="st-flag">⚑ live tension</span></h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">AI must not substitute for the care and work only human beings can do for one another. The room agrees on the principle; where the substitution line sits is contested.</p>
          {{ evcard(68, "Grounding: learn to be human first") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R5 — Healthy use is learned, not patched</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Learning to use AI healthily cannot be outsourced to model changes; education and practice are part of governance.</p>
          {{ evcard(74, "Grounding: education entrusted to AI") }}{{ evcard(80, "Grounding: model changes can't replace learning") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R6 — Community authorship</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Communities can build or shape AI tuned to their own values and teachings, with each member seeing their own data first.</p>
          {{ evcard(15, "Grounding: if my community built one, I'd want in") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R7 — Worldview provenance disclosure</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Disclose when a response originates from a particular worldview, and whose values the defaults average over.</p>
          {{ evcard(62, "Grounding: knowledge acquired through a lens") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R8 — What we confide deserves protection</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Strict, auditable limits on who accesses what people put into AI; AI-enabled surveillance treated as a first-order harm.</p>
          {{ evcard(25, "Grounding: autonomy and consent") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R9 — Homogenization as a governance harm</h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">Flattening individuality and minority voices into an average is a harm governance names and measures.</p>
          {{ evcard(70, "Grounding: the tyranny of the majority, aggregated") }}</li>
        <li class="st-ballot-item"><h4 class="font-bold">R10 — The right not to be known <span class="st-flag">⚑ live tension</span></h4>
          <p class="text-size--1 mb-2">An effective, penalty-free right to keep AI out of one's inner, moral, and spiritual life — protecting equally those who choose to invite it in.</p>
          {{ evcard(33, "Grounding: no role in spirituality — the contested pole") }}</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- honest limits ---------- #}
  <section id="limits" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <h2 class="mb-4">Honest limits</h2>
      <div class="gr-prose text-size--2" style="color: #6c6c6c">
        <p class="mb-2">This was one session: {{ CP.stats.voters }} self-selected participants, English-language, virtual. It offers depth of standpoint, not statistical representativeness — and a participant raised the language point from inside the room: “{{ ST["77"].text }}” ({{ counts(ST["77"].total) }}).</p>
        <p class="mb-2">Opinion clustering at this scale is unstable, and we disclose it rather than hide it: the same votes clustered into four groups at 09:00 and effectively two by 15:05, with zero votes changed (Act 2 shows it happening). Instability is a property of the method at ~{{ CP.stats.voters }} voters, not an error in the data — which is why this page's claims rest on vote-defined cohorts, not group labels.</p>
        <p class="mb-2">The format has limits a participant named directly — “{{ ST["82"].text }}” ({{ counts(ST["82"].total) }}). Statement 83 arrived too late to gather votes ({{ ST["83"].total.votes }} cast). The facilitator's seed account sits inside bloc A's count of {{ CP.method.blocs.A }}; it cast only pass votes. The official clustering also contains a 2-member statistical leftover we do not characterize, shown as “other” in visuals.</p>
        <p>Two export snapshots of this conversation exist (09:00 and 15:05); the fuller 15:05 export ({{ CP.stats.total_votes_display }} votes) governs every number on this page. Both are downloadable below.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- read the data yourself ---------- #}
  <section id="data" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <h2 class="mb-4">Read the data yourself</h2>
      <p class="gr-prose mb-3">The full record: every statement voted on in the deliberation — three non-substantive entries excluded (“Agree”, a test message, and “Not enough time, sorry”) — with room-wide tallies and each bloc's agree rate, from the 15:05 export. Sort and filter, or just read; the table works without JavaScript too.</p>
      <p class="gr-legend mb-4"><span>◔ = thin data: fewer than 5 votes cast in that bloc; treat as directional. Thin cells are greyed.</span></p>
      <div id="gr-filters" class="flex flex-wrap gap-2 mb-4" hidden>
        <button type="button" class="gr-filter" data-sort="id" data-dir="asc" aria-pressed="true">In order</button>
        <button type="button" class="gr-filter" data-sort="minagree" data-dir="desc" aria-pressed="false">Most consensus</button>
        <button type="button" class="gr-filter" data-sort="passrate" data-dir="desc" aria-pressed="false">Most passed</button>
      </div>
      <div class="gr-table-wrap">
        <table class="gr-table" id="gr-explorer-table">
          <thead>
            <tr>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="id">#</th>
              <th scope="col" data-key="text">Statement</th>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="agrees">Agree</th>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="disagrees">Disagree</th>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="passes">Pass</th>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="ga" title="Bloc A agree rate"><span class="gr-text-A">A</span>&nbsp;agree</th>
              <th scope="col" class="gr-num" data-key="gc" title="Bloc C agree rate"><span class="gr-text-C">C</span>&nbsp;agree</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            {% for key, s in ST %}
            {% if not s.noise and s.text %}
            <tr
              id="s{{ s.id }}"
              data-id="{{ s.id }}"
              data-agrees="{{ s.total.agrees }}"
              data-disagrees="{{ s.total.disagrees }}"
              data-passes="{{ s.total.passes }}"
              data-passrate="{{ (s.total.passes / s.total.votes) | round(4) if s.total.votes else -1 }}"
              data-minagree="{{ s.min_bloc_agree_rate if s.min_bloc_agree_rate != null else -1 }}"
              data-ga="{{ s.blocs.A.agree_rate if s.blocs.A.votes > 0 else -1 }}"
              data-gc="{{ s.blocs.C.agree_rate if s.blocs.C.votes > 0 else -1 }}"
            >
              <td class="gr-num">{{ s.id }}</td>
              <td><span class="gr-stmt-text">{{ s.text }}</span> <span class="gr-badge {% if s.source == 'live' %}text-black{% else %}text-gray{% endif %}">{{ "written live" if s.source == "live" else "seed" }}</span></td>
              <td class="gr-num">{{ s.total.agrees }}</td>
              <td class="gr-num">{{ s.total.disagrees }}</td>
              <td class="gr-num">{{ s.total.passes }}</td>
              {% for b in ["A", "C"] %}
              {% set t = s.blocs[b] %}
              <td class="gr-num{% if t.thin %} gr-cell-thin{% endif %}" title="Bloc {{ b }}: {{ counts(t) }}">{% if t.votes > 0 %}{{ (t.agree_rate * 100) | round }}%{% else %}–{% endif %}{{ thin(t) }}</td>
              {% endfor %}
            </tr>
            {% endif %}
            {% endfor %}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
      <p class="gr-counts mt-3 mb-8">“Most consensus” ranks by the lowest agree rate across blocs A and C (a statement ranks high only if both blocs backed it). Statement 83 gathered {{ ST["83"].total.votes }} votes before the export and is excluded from ranked orderings. Tallies are computed from the 15:05 participant-vote matrix; the statement-text export is authoritative for wording. The facilitator seed account (20 votes, all passes) is included in bloc A. Blocs map from Pol.is group-ids 0 (A) and 2 (C); the 2-member group 1 and two unclustered voters appear in room-wide totals only.</p>

      <h3 class="mb-2">Downloads</h3>
      <ul class="st-downloads mb-2">
        <li><a class="underline" href="/files/geneva-reflections/computed.json">computed.json</a> — every number on this page, with method notes</li>
        <li><a class="underline" href="/files/geneva-reflections/{{ CP.export }}-participant-votes.csv">15:05 vote matrix (CSV)</a> · <a class="underline" href="/files/geneva-reflections/{{ CP.export }}-comment-groups.csv">15:05 statements (CSV)</a></li>
        <li><a class="underline" href="/files/geneva-reflections/{{ CP.earlier_export }}-participant-votes.csv">09:00 vote matrix (CSV)</a> · <a class="underline" href="/files/geneva-reflections/{{ CP.earlier_export }}-comment-groups.csv">09:00 statements (CSV)</a></li>
      </ul>
      <p class="gr-counts">Anyone can audit the pipeline: <span class="gr-stmt-text">scripts/story_compute.py</span> in the site's repository regenerates computed.json from the CSVs.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ---------- coda ---------- #}
  <section id="coda" class="grid grid-cols-layout-4 lg:grid-cols-layout-12 pb-16 st-act">
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-1 lg:col-end-gutter-9">
      <p class="gr-prose mb-6">What this small room produced — a floor of shared red lines, a principled fork over remedies, and two tensions it chose to keep rather than resolve by majority — is early evidence that a community can surface its own common knowledge about AI. That is a first step toward communities authoring and governing AI on their own terms, the direction RadicalxChange explores as <a class="underline" href="https://www.plurality.net/">Plurality</a>. The next step is the quadratic-voting stage, which prices how much the community will spend on each principle — especially the two built on the tensions the room refused to resolve.</p>
      {% if C.footer.rwg_signup_url %}
      <p class="text-size--1"><a class="underline font-bold" href="{{ C.footer.rwg_signup_url }}">{{ C.footer.rwg_signup_label }} →</a> <span class="gr-counts">or write to <a class="underline" href="mailto:{{ C.footer.contact_email }}">{{ C.footer.contact_email }}</a></span></p>
      {% endif %}
    </div>
    <div class="col-span-columns lg:col-start-column-10 lg:col-end-margin-2">
      <p class="gr-counts mb-2">{{ C.footer.polis_credit }} <a class="underline" href="{{ C.footer.polis_url }}">pol.is</a></p>
      <p class="gr-counts">Convened by {% for cv in C.hero.conveners %}{{ cv.name }}{% if not loop.last %} · {% endif %}{% endfor %} — <a class="underline" href="{{ C.footer.event_page_url }}">about the event</a>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

</main>

{{ footer.render() }}

